          <!-- Content -->

          <article>
            <header>
              <h2>Movement as Medicine: How Physical Activity Affects Your Mood</h2>
            </header>

            <p>In a world that's moving faster and faster, we often forget one of the simplest ways to care for our mental health — movement. Regular physical activity might be the key to feeling better.</p>

            <h2>What Happens to Your Brain When You Move?</h2>

            <h6>Endorphins — Your Natural Happiness Hormones</h6>
            <p>Just 20 minutes of moderate physical effort triggers your brain to release endorphins, which act like natural antidepressants.</p>

            <h6>Better Sleep</h6>
            <p>Movement helps regulate your circadian rhythm, making it easier to fall asleep and stay asleep. And better sleep = better mood.</p>

            <h6>More Energy and Motivation</h6>
            <p>Regular exercise boosts your daily energy levels and improves focus.</p>

            <h6>Stress and Tension Relief</h6>
            <p>Physical exertion helps release built-up emotions. Running, yoga, cycling — any form of movement acts as a "reset" for your nervous system.</p>

            <h2>You Don’t Have to Hit the Gym Right Away</h2>

            <p>It’s not about running marathons (unless that’s your thing!). It’s about movement that suits you and your capabilities.</p>
            <p>🔹 A walk after work</p>
            <p>🔹 Stretching to music</p>
            <p>🔹 A short yoga session on YouTube</p>
            <p>🔹 Dancing in the kitchen!</p>
            <p>🔹 10 push-ups and squats between tasks</p>
            <p>The important thing is to start — even with just a few minutes a day.</p>

            <h2>With EchoMood You Can:</h2>
            <h6>Add physical activity to your mood journal</h6>
            <h6>See how it affects your mental state</h6>
            <h6>Stay motivated with visual progress reports</h6>

            <h2>One Small Step. A Big Impact.</h2>
            <p>Movement is more than just about appearance — it’s a form of self-care.</p>
            <p>Let your body and mind work together again.</p>
          </article>

